{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Lubyanka Criminal Group | image = Lubyanka Criminal Group.jpg | image_size = 220px | alt = | caption = | author = [[Alexander Litvinenko]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = Лубянская преступная группировка | orig_lang_code = ru | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | release_number = | subject = [[Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation|Russian Security Services]] | genre = | set_in = | publisher = GRANI | publisher2 = | pub_date = 2002 | english_pub_date = | published = | media_type = | pages = 255 pp. | awards = | isbn = 978-0-9723878-0-4 | isbn_note = | oclc = 51485973 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }}
'''''Lubyanka Criminal Group''''' ({{lang-ru|Лубянская преступная группировка}}; also translated as ''The Gang from Lubyanka'') is a book by [[Alexander Litvinenko]] about the alleged transformation of the [[Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation|Russian Security Services]] into a criminal and terrorist organization.<ref>{{harvnb|Litvinenko|2002}}</ref><ref name="group">[http://old.prima-news.ru/eng/news/articles/2002/9/30/17082.html The FSB as a criminal grouping] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20110823155751/http://old.prima-news.ru/eng/news/articles/2002/9/30/17082.html |date=2011-08-23 }}, Andrei Antonov, [[Prima News]], 2002-09-30</ref>
[[Lubyanka (KGB)|Lubyanka]] is known as [[KGB]] headquarters. In the book, the authors claim that Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]] and other [[Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation|FSB]] officers have been involved in organized crime, including covering up [[drug traffic]] from [[Afghanistan]].<ref> [http://prima-news.ru/eng/news/news/2002/10/11/17326.html Litvinenko accuses president Putin of involvement in drug business] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092620/http://prima-news.ru/eng/news/news/2002/10/11/17326.html |date=2007-09-29 }}, by [[Prima (news agency)|Prima News]]</ref>
The book was withdrawn from sales in Russia by request from the [[Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation|FSB]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110823155844/http://old.prima-news.ru/eng/news/news/2004/1/30/27326.html State secret disclosed in the book about terrorist acts], [[Prima (news agency)|Prima News]]</ref> according to The Moscow Human Rights News Agency [[Prima (news agency)|Prima News]]. In response, the authors allowed the book's publication and distribution by anyone in Russia free of charge. [[Alexander Goldfarb (microbiologist)|Alexander Goldfarb]], the executive director of [[International Foundation for Civil Liberties]] which licensed the book's copyright in Russia, stated, "By banning the books for the first time since the Soviet times, FSB threw down a challenge to the society".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111007033412/http://old.prima-news.ru/eng/news/news/2004/2/1/27343.html Copyright removed from books by Litvinenko and Felshtinskiy], [[Prima (news agency)|Prima News]]</ref>
Former Interior Minister of Russia [[Anatoly Kulikov]] promised to bring a libel suit against the book but did not follow it through.<ref name="Dissident">{{harvnb|Goldfarb|Litvinenko|2007|pp=268–269}}</ref>
==Reception== [[Viktor Suvorov]], author of ''[[Icebreaker (Suvorov)|Icebreaker]]'' said that the book is "Terrifying, gripping and instructive".<ref name="group"/> According to Suvorov: {{Quotation|1=Litvinenko described a leading criminal group that provides "protection" for all other organized crime in the country and which continues the criminal war against their own people", like their [[KGB]] and [[NKVD]] predecessors. "Book proves: Lubyanka was taken over by the [[enemies of the people]] (who else would put their own people on the needle and [[Russian apartment bombings|blow up sleeping children]]?)"<ref>[http://www.suvorov.com/books/unpublished/a001.htm Why United States do not have "external intelligence"?], by [[Viktor Suvorov]]</ref> "If Putin's team can not disprove the facts provided by Litvinenko, Putin must shoot himself. [[Nikolai Patrushev|Patrushev]] and all other leadership of Lubyanka Criminal Group must follow his example.}}
Former Soviet [[prisoner of conscience]] [[Vladimir Bukovsky]] stated, "Litvinenko eloquently depicts that what was long considered to be the 'shield and sword' of the communist party is in reality a huge criminal mechanism".<ref name="group"/>
As Andrei Antonov writes, "the way Litvinenko sees it, the FSB is clearly a criminal and even terrorist organization. And not only because of [[Russian apartment bombings|apartment explosions]] or alleged conspiracy against [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Berezovsky]]. Litvinenko is certain that security services were behind the murder of [[Galina Starovoitova]], a prominent figure in Russia's democracy movement, and the death of [[Anatoly Sobchak]], and many, many other things."<ref name="group"/>
Alan Cowell praised the book as an important source that described the attempted assassination of [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]] in Moscow and many other events.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/03/world/europe/03russian.html?pagewanted=print Russian Ex-Spy Lived in a World of Deceptions], by Alan Cowell, [[New York Times]], December 3, 2006 </ref>
